Q. What will happen from now on?

A. The Department of State has announced its intention to revise, presumably in record time, the regulations concerning Cuba. Some travel companies have already shown a strong interest in expanding tourism to Cuba. Next year will probably be important to the Cuban economy because thousands of Americans will visit the country regardless of the limitations.

Q. At Haven in Havana, you have a very touristy profile: you talk about cruising and cigar-tasting, and especially about drinking rum .What is it from the inside that you think tourists will be interested in that will immediately attract them, without having to go into the minutiae of the current political and ideological situation?

A.Due to the limited quantity of Americans visiting Cuba, it's essential for their visit to feel excellent and satisfy the desires and needs of creativity. These people are not crazy; they're very sensible and look for logical investments to meet a demand. All that is needed is getting organized at a national level, one that is similar to that that was in place under the protocol of 1998/1999, which I don't think has been repeated ever since.

Q. What are your ideas in that sense?
